WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:20.390
&gt;&gt; Karyn Temple Claggett:
Thank you and welcome

00:00:20.390 --> 00:00:23.800
to the Coolidge Auditorium
as we celebrate World IP Day,

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:25.950
Innovation Improving Lives.

00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:29.260
My name is Karyn Temple Claggett
and I'm currently Acting Register

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:31.060
of the US Copyright Office.

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:33.980
We are pleased to once
again this year partner

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:35.850
with the Copyright
Alliance on this event

00:00:35.850 --> 00:00:38.880
and we are particularly
thrilled to have a special guest,

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.200
Representative Doug Collins,

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:43.260
who I will formally
introduce in just a moment.

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:47.360
But first, I want to take a moment
to reflect on this year's theme

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:49.410
from a copyright perspective.

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:53.460
We know that copyrighted
works such as books, films,

00:00:53.460 --> 00:00:59.040
and music entertain the world but
do they actually improve lives,

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:02.740
as the theme of this year's
World IP Day celebrates?

00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:05.350
Well, I expect for most
of us in the audience

00:01:05.350 --> 00:01:07.820
that question is a rhetorical one.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.620
Whether it is the way that
copyrighted works inspire us

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:16.330
like the iconic photograph of the
first female Boston Marathon runner

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:20.080
by Harry Trask, or the
way they impact change

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:23.090
in the political environment
like the groundbreaking novel,

00:01:23.090 --> 00:01:27.990
The Jungle, by Upton Sinclair, or
the way they humanize the struggle

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:31.470
for equality such as
the searing photograph

00:01:31.470 --> 00:01:35.150
of Emmett Till's open
casket in Jet Magazine,

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:40.120
copyrighted works improve our
lives in immeasurable ways.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:42.870
They make us laugh,
they make us think,

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:46.130
and in many instances,
they make us act.

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:49.390
In fact, copyrighted works can
actually impact our very health

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:50.690
and well-being.

00:01:50.690 --> 00:01:53.440
According to one study,
listening to music prior

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.200
to surgery actually lowered
patient's anxiety better

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:58.680
than medication.

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:02.950
Another study pointed out something
I think we all know inherently

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:05.960
and probably have heard from
our parents since kindergarten,

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:09.200
that reading a novel enhances
connectivity in the brain

00:02:09.200 --> 00:02:11.220
and improves brain function.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:14.120
Simply put, it makes us smarter.

00:02:14.120 --> 00:02:16.630
As a CNN article recently
acknowledged,

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:20.710
books can literally
change your life.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.830
Even videogames, which
are often seen by parents

00:02:24.830 --> 00:02:27.770
as really just mere
child's play can,

00:02:27.770 --> 00:02:30.520
according to the American
Psychological Association,

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:35.830
strengthen cognitive skills such
as reason, memory, and perception

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:40.170
and copyrighted works such as
software directly improve lives

00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:43.380
by allowing people with
disabilities to access the world

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:45.710
in ways never imaginable before.

00:02:45.710 --> 00:02:49.850
Software allows those
with amputated, paralyzed,

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:54.720 position:56%
or impaired limbs to operate
computers and navigate the internet.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.330
It can magnify and read
text on computer screens

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:00.550
for those with sight impairments.

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:04.130
In short, innovative
software has opened the door

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:07.360
to an entirely new world of
knowledge for many who thought

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:11.140
that certain life experiences
were forever lost.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.950
So, while this year's
theme for World IP Day,

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:17.430
Innovation Improving Lives may
not have immediately brought

00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:21.490
to mind the role of copyright and
copyrighted works in our society,

00:03:21.490 --> 00:03:26.150
it is fact very fitting description
of how important copyright

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:30.620
and copyrighted works are to our
culture and our everyday lives

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:35.430 position:56%
because of course, without copyright
law which gives artists, authors

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:39.000
and other creators the ability
to actually make a living

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.770
in the pursuit of their creativity,
many of our most iconic songs,

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:47.280
films, and books simply
would not exist.

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:52.000
For example, it was a full-time
photojournalist who took that photo

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.320
of Kathrine Switzer running
the Boston Marathon in 1967,

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:00.950
that impacted and inspired female
runners for many years to come.

00:04:00.950 --> 00:04:05.950
It was a full-time writer who
wrote the iconic book, The Jungle,

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:09.520
which encouraged concrete
legislative changes

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:13.610
for the US workforce and
it took hundreds of workers

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:17.060
in the film industry, all
supported by copyright law

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:21.490
to complete the groundbreaking
films Norma Rae, Philadelphia,

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:25.100
The Thin Blue Line, and
Moonlight and many, many others,

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:28.480
which have inspired
and touched thousands.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:31.060
Copyright, as the Supreme
Court has stated,

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:36.810 position:56%
is the engine of free expression and
sometimes it is even more than that.

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:41.880 position:56%
Many creators have used their
copyrights to directly improve lives

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:45.100
through a wide variety
of charitable endeavors.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:48.450
For example, Anne Frank's
father registered her copyright

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:52.250
but the proceeds of the sale of The
Diary of Anne Frank have been used

00:04:52.250 --> 00:04:56.090
to fund The Anne Frank
Foundation's charitable initiatives

00:04:56.090 --> 00:05:00.100
and many musicians have often
banded together to create

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.270
and perform benefit songs.

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:04.900
The famous song, We Are
The World for example,

00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:09.480
raised more than 75 million
dollars for famine relief.

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:13.210
Finally, as the examples you'll see
during the discussion later today

00:05:13.210 --> 00:05:16.610
demonstrate, artists
often use technology

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:19.410
and other innovative
tools themselves

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:23.360
to improve their own
creativity and artistry.

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:27.560
So again, while it may not have
been quite obvious at first glance,

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:32.270
this year's theme for World IP
Day is perfectly, perfectly suited

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:37.510
to celebrate copyright
as we know it today.

00:05:37.510 --> 00:05:47.130
[ Applause ]

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:50.140
&gt;&gt; Karyn Temple Claggett : And with
that as a backdrop, we are honored

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:54.700
to have with us someone who has
championed and supported copyright

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:58.720
