00:59:56.430 --> 00:59:58.490
whether the hair stood up
on the back of your neck.

00:59:58.490 --> 01:00:02.240
That's actually how music is moving
you, it's moving through space,

01:00:02.240 --> 01:00:05.830
it's vibrational, it's effecting
you on a vibrational level

01:00:05.830 --> 01:00:10.110
so I'm really attracted to that
aspect of music, which is very hard

01:00:10.110 --> 01:00:12.390
to talk about because we don't
have really a physical language

01:00:12.390 --> 01:00:14.570
to discuss it, but
it is so essential

01:00:14.570 --> 01:00:18.050
to the cultural power of music.

01:00:18.050 --> 01:00:21.650
I just finished liner notes
for the R&amp;B artist D'Angelo,

01:00:21.650 --> 01:00:24.480
it's a boxed set that's
coming out of his 90s albums

01:00:24.480 --> 01:00:27.670
and he was particularly influenced
in terms of the rhythm of some

01:00:27.670 --> 01:00:32.180
of his work by a hip-hop producer
named J Dilla, who passed away,

01:00:32.180 --> 01:00:34.670
but J Dilla was one of the most
influential producers in hip-hop

01:00:34.670 --> 01:00:38.750
over the last 20, 30 years and one
of the things that J Dilla was good

01:00:38.750 --> 01:00:41.880
at was making sure that
when he would program drums,

01:00:41.880 --> 01:00:43.730
in other words not using
an actual live drum set

01:00:43.730 --> 01:00:47.530
but actually using drum samples,
you can go into recording software

01:00:47.530 --> 01:00:49.310
and actually line up the samples

01:00:49.310 --> 01:00:53.240
and you can use a tool
that's called quantization

01:00:53.240 --> 01:00:57.440
where you can actually quantize the
beat and make sure it lands exactly

01:00:57.440 --> 01:00:59.920
on the measures that you want
so instead of having kind

01:00:59.920 --> 01:01:02.770
of sloppy drumming, you
can have exact drumming

01:01:02.770 --> 01:01:06.410
and J Dilla was notorious
for actually moving all

01:01:06.410 --> 01:01:08.630
of his drum samples
just a little bit off

01:01:08.630 --> 01:01:14.860
so the sound is a little bit wonky
and kind of lurching and loping,

01:01:14.860 --> 01:01:17.680
but it actually changed the
sound of hip-hop in the 1990s

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:20.640
and everybody wanted the J Dilla
sound and it actually is the sound

01:01:20.640 --> 01:01:23.250
that empowers all of
D'Angelo's records

01:01:23.250 --> 01:01:25.710
and he's won R&amp;B Grammy's
for most of his records.

01:01:25.710 --> 01:01:27.710
We'd always go in and
make sure it has this kind

01:01:27.710 --> 01:01:31.940
of what he would call inebriated
sort of sloppy drunken feeling

01:01:31.940 --> 01:01:33.710
to the beats and it makes no sense.

01:01:33.710 --> 01:01:36.070
Why should a beat not
actually hit exactly right

01:01:36.070 --> 01:01:39.260
on where you want it to,
but the whole point was

01:01:39.260 --> 01:01:44.940 position:56%
to do it deliberately to incorporate
the mistakes deliberately

01:01:44.940 --> 01:01:48.170
to create a particular feeling
that would be powerful for people.

01:01:48.170 --> 01:01:50.810
&gt;&gt; Steve Bogard: You can
actually get tempo maps

01:01:50.810 --> 01:01:52.800
for various drummers,
whichever drum.

01:01:52.800 --> 01:01:56.700 position:56%
If you want Muscle Shoals behind
the beat you can get a Roger Hawkins

01:01:56.700 --> 01:01:58.000
tempo map.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:01:59.500
If you want a jazzier Steve Gadd-

01:01:59.500 --> 01:02:02.400
&gt;&gt; Eric Schwartz: And only
Purdie can do the Purdie shuffle.

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:05.040
&gt;&gt; Steve Bogard: Only Purdie
can do that, he's the only one.

01:02:05.040 --> 01:02:08.670
&gt;&gt; Eric Schwartz: But you know,
there are some imperfections

01:02:08.670 --> 01:02:12.430
and then there are also the
individual performances and part

01:02:12.430 --> 01:02:16.160 position:56%
of this also is the role of the
producer in putting it all together,

01:02:16.160 --> 01:02:19.240
when you break down
tracks and we've done that,

01:02:19.240 --> 01:02:22.940 position:56%
we did that at The Copyright Society
a few years ago with Superstition,

01:02:22.940 --> 01:02:27.840
and you listen to Stevie Wonder's
three recordings of the keyboard

01:02:27.840 --> 01:02:33.400
and none of them are perfect by
any means, but that's what happens

01:02:33.400 --> 01:02:36.870
in the mixing and in the producing.

01:02:36.870 --> 01:02:41.860
We're putting them together, no one
can say that song's not as close

01:02:41.860 --> 01:02:45.190
to perfection as it could
be emotionally whether

01:02:45.190 --> 01:02:51.510
or not musically, even someone as
adept as Stevie Wonder would be.

01:02:51.510 --> 01:02:55.680
So last question and then looking
at our time, we need to wrap

01:02:55.680 --> 01:02:58.990
up our lessons for
up and coming artists

01:02:58.990 --> 01:03:02.920
in this day and age of tough music.

01:03:02.920 --> 01:03:07.230
I'll start with you and so
what are the lessons for an up

01:03:07.230 --> 01:03:09.820
and coming songwriter/performer?

01:03:09.820 --> 01:03:12.020 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Steve Bogard: First and foremost,
and I think we've covered some

01:03:12.020 --> 01:03:14.760 position:56%
of this, is you have to move people.

01:03:14.760 --> 01:03:20.360
You have to create something that
moves people and I'd like to see

01:03:20.360 --> 01:03:23.710
from the pop perspective it's
more like I'm cooler than you,

01:03:23.710 --> 01:03:25.290
wouldn't you like to be me?

01:03:25.290 --> 01:03:29.150
From a country perspective, it's
more like my mom gets sick too,

01:03:29.150 --> 01:03:30.800
we're having coffee
at the kitchen table.

01:03:30.800 --> 01:03:35.410
It's just two funnels that
go two different directions

01:03:35.410 --> 01:03:40.110
but for new artists, I'd say
concentrate on the emotion,

01:03:40.110 --> 01:03:44.690
concentrate on, I had a kid at
a Bluebird gig show me a tattoo

01:03:44.690 --> 01:03:47.910
that said, "Every mile a memory"
and he and his buddy went to Iraq

01:03:47.910 --> 01:03:50.910
and that's a song I wrote
that Dierks Bentley did and he

01:03:50.910 --> 01:03:53.720
and his buddy went to Iraq
and they said they were going

01:03:53.720 --> 01:03:55.150
to make memories and
come back together,

01:03:55.150 --> 01:03:56.960
and his buddy didn't come home.

01:03:56.960 --> 01:04:02.670
So, if you can find ways to
communicate that kind of emotion

01:04:02.670 --> 01:04:09.310
and then secondly, I'd say in this
current climate hedge your bets.

01:04:09.310 --> 01:04:10.610
Be a producer, be a
performer, be a singer,

01:04:10.610 --> 01:04:13.510
or make friends with
all of the above.

01:04:13.510 --> 01:04:19.040
[ Laughter ]

01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:20.340
&gt;&gt; Eric Schwartz: And Jason?

01:04:20.340 --> 01:04:22.610
&gt;&gt; Jason King: You know, I'm
director at a music school

01:04:22.610 --> 01:04:24.420
so I'm constantly giving
advice to students,

01:04:24.420 --> 01:04:28.110
that's literally the nature of the
classes we do but I think I agree

01:04:28.110 --> 01:04:31.070
with Steve, I think part of
it is you need to be able

01:04:31.070 --> 01:04:35.200
to connect what you do to your
passion so in other words,

01:04:35.200 --> 01:04:37.240
a lot of our students
get into a state

01:04:37.240 --> 01:04:39.550
where they are just thinking
okay, what's on the charts,

01:04:39.550 --> 01:04:44.290
how can I be successful by sort
of gaming the system but really,

01:04:44.290 --> 01:04:49.070
the most amazing music is some
of the most eccentric, singular,

01:04:49.070 --> 01:04:52.030
idiosyncratic music so think of
a song like Bohemian Rhapsody,

01:04:52.030 --> 01:04:53.980
I'm writing a book
on Freddie Mercury

01:04:53.980 --> 01:04:56.970
so there's a song that
follows no rules.

01:04:56.970 --> 01:04:59.800
It doesn't even have a chorus,
it's like, seven minutes long,

01:04:59.800 --> 01:05:01.590
it's strange, it's
unusual, but it's one

01:05:01.590 --> 01:05:03.330
of the top pop songs of all time.

01:05:03.330 --> 01:05:09.030
It doesn't follow a formula,
so I think getting young people

01:05:09.030 --> 01:05:13.350
to be able to reach deep into
their bones, into the marrow

01:05:13.350 --> 01:05:17.450
of their bones and pull something
out is so meaningful to them,

01:05:17.450 --> 01:05:21.850
that's the first step, being able
to connect deeply to what you do.

01:05:21.850 --> 01:05:24.250
Second, I also think it's really
important to learn your craft.

01:05:24.250 --> 01:05:26.410
I think craft is a word that
we just don't use enough

01:05:26.410 --> 01:05:31.540
and it's really important to hone
your craft, to be able to develop,

01:05:31.540 --> 01:05:34.880
and to shape your work over time,
and to fail and to make mistakes,

01:05:34.880 --> 01:05:37.500
and to learn from those
mistakes and so on.

01:05:37.500 --> 01:05:39.800
And also, I think it's really
important for young performers

01:05:39.800 --> 01:05:44.100
to learn the business, that it
is a business, it's not just show

01:05:44.100 --> 01:05:46.830
and that they should empower
themselves by learning how

01:05:46.830 --> 01:05:51.320
to write contracts, read
contracts, learn how revenue flows

01:05:51.320 --> 01:05:53.820
through a system, learn
how to protect themselves,

01:05:53.820 --> 01:05:57.060 position:56%
and all of those kinds of things and
when I think you marry that approach

01:05:57.060 --> 01:05:58.990
to being a really talented artist

01:05:58.990 --> 01:06:03.350
with being a really savvy business
person, I think you can do wonders.

01:06:03.350 --> 01:06:07.060
&gt;&gt; Eric Schwartz: Sound advice
and the craft part is the hardest,

01:06:07.060 --> 01:06:09.090 position:56%
I think, to communicate to students.

01:06:09.090 --> 01:06:13.020
Every writer I know, and I've
known a lot over my career

01:06:13.020 --> 01:06:15.150
as a copyright lawyer,
gets up every day

01:06:15.150 --> 01:06:20.450
at some point they have a schedule
and they write and you know,

01:06:20.450 --> 01:06:24.990
90 percent of it no one ever sees
but it's improving the craft.

01:06:24.990 --> 01:06:28.280
I've always thought too it's the
reason why copyright term was

01:06:28.280 --> 01:06:31.200
as long as it was because
there are exceptions.

01:06:31.200 --> 01:06:38.390
John Lennon died at 40, but most
artists of any kind, writers,

01:06:38.390 --> 01:06:43.820 position:56%
songwriters, performers, get better
as they age, as their craft improves

01:06:43.820 --> 01:06:51.080
and so you have that
term to recognize that.

